\section{Numerical results and discussions}
In this section, ($\mathrm{I}$) we carry out the frequency-domain solution on the control set of SMC to recognize how the resulting eigenvalue and eigenfunction can correspond to the time-domain evolution of transient variables.
($\mathrm{II}$) By understanding frequency-domain analysis, we can continue to investigate the underlying mechanisms of rhythmicity by varying dosages of agonists (KCl) for emerging calcium oscillations; otherwise, time-domain analysis is performed to get intuitional ideas of synchronized timings  among signaling pathways, and this action also validates our approach.
($\mathrm{III}$) Lastly, we involve intercellular calcium dynamics in finite SMC clusters and attempt to explore physiological functionalities of the rhythmic oscillations of SMCs.

Mathematical algorithms were implemented in Visual C++ and were executed on HP Z800 workstation with 48GB of RAM. Relevant default values of the variables and initial parameters are defined in appendix \ref{appa}. Source codes of C++ language for time-domain and frequency-domain analyses are available online: https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B8l8iii7Z4iqWWJRLTduRl9zMVE. We also refer to JSim computations for time-domain programming: http://www.physiome.org/jsim/.

\subsection{Understanding the frequency-domain approach on the control set of SMC}
Parameters for the control set of SMC are shown in appendix \ref{appa}, except $[K]_e=35.8mM$, $[NE]=2.0\times 10^{-4}mM$, $I_{SERCA,0}=20.4pA$, and $R_{leak}=0.0000535$. Equilibrium parameters $\vec{\overline{\delta}}_{\nu}$ necessary for frequency-domain analysis are obtained by running the time-domain simulation for $10^5s$. Numerical results as discussed below show good agreement with the experimental observation \cite{KClexp1}: KCl stimulation of isolated rat mesenteric arteriole-induced vasomotion with a 25-second period and a $[K^{+}]_e$ threshold of $20mM$.

Figure (\ref{fig2}) shows numerical solutions for the control set of SMC, which are classified into four categories: ($\mathrm{a}$) Real part of eigenvalues that infers the growing time or decaying time of eigenmodes, corresponding to positive or negative values, respectively; ($\mathrm{b}$) Imaginary part of eigenvalues that indicates the oscillation period of the eigenmode; ($\mathrm{c}$) Amplitude of components in the specified (oscillating) eigenmode that gives the weighting of the corresponding component variable; and ($\mathrm{d}$) Phase of components in eigenmode that tells the relative phase lags regarding oscillations. Each amplitude value of components in Fig (\ref{fig2}c) is divided by its own average and is dimensionless.

In Figs. (\ref{fig2}a-\ref{fig2}b), two sets of mutually complex-conjugate eigenvalues, with values $-0.028\pm 0.011i$ and $-8\cdot10^{-7} \pm 0.000264i$ $ms^{-1}$, are distinguished as eigenmodes $(5,6)$ and $(22,23)$, respectively. The latter value signifies a decay time of $1250s$ and an oscillation period of $23.8s$ for the set of eigenmodes $(22,23)$.

In Figs. (\ref{fig2}c-\ref{fig2}d), we further analyze the amplitude and phase for the oscillating eigenmode $(22,23)$. Several quantities are selected for our study: the oscillation amplitude of component $[Ca]_i$ is $22\%$, the oscillation amplitude of component $[Ca]_u$ is $10\%$, and the phase difference between $[Ca]_i$ and $[Ca]_u$ is $105^{o}$.

To recognize these quantities by frequency-domain analysis, we conduct the time-domain analysis on the same conditions as shown in Fig. (\ref{fig3}).
\begin{figure*}[ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{fig2.eps}
\caption{ Numerical analysis of eigenvalues and the oscillating eigenmodes (22 and 23) for the control-set SMC.}\label{fig2}
\end{figure*}

Figure (\ref{fig3}a) shows the temporal changes of $[Ca^{2+}]_i$ to arrive at the equilibrium. With the given equilibrium condition, the properties of calcium oscillation in cytosol (blue curve) are investigated via a transient stimulation as in Fig. (\ref{fig3}a), which depict agreeable results to decaying time $1/\omega_{22,r}=-1250s$ in Fig. (\ref{fig2}a) and to oscillation period $2\pi/\omega_{22,c}=24s$ in Fig. (\ref{fig2}b). An alternative experimental set (red curve), with $[K^{+}]_e=40mM$, is added here to explain about the high dosages of agonists $KCl$ in the next paragraph.

Figures. (\ref{fig3}c-\ref{fig3}d) characterize the oscillation amplitude and phase for several transient variables via temporal curves. Here, each curve is divided by the corresponding average of variables to benefit from a comparison with Figs. (\ref{fig2}c-\ref{fig2}d), e.g. $22\%$ oscillation amplitude of $[Ca]_i$ relatively compared to $10\%$ oscillation amplitude of $[Ca]_u$, and $105^{o}$ phase lags between $[Ca]_i$ and $[Ca]_u$.

\begin{figure*}[ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.375]{fig3.eps}
\caption{ Time domain analysis for the control-set SMC after equilibrium. }\label{fig3}
\end{figure*}

\subsection{Time-domain and frequency-domain analyses for single SMC}

 With an understanding of the frequency-domain approach, we continue to investigate the underlying rhythmicity of SMC by varying dosages of agonists (KCl) for emerging calcium oscillations. Figure (\ref{fig4}) shows the eigenvalue spectrum of single SMC in response to different extracellular potassium concentrations, in which the spectrum is depicted by time for our demonstrations. For real parts of eigenvalues in Fig. (\ref{fig4}a), two sets of mutually complex-conjugate solutions corresponding to rhythmic oscillations are found: ($\mathrm{a}$) The set of eigenmode $(5,6)$ (green curves) characterizes a short oscillation period ($\sim1s$), fast decay time ($\sim0.1s$), and insensitivity against agonist. This mode emerges even under very low dosages of agonists. As stated in the literature \cite{vasoa3}, rat mesenteric arteries, are resistant to vasomotion and require
induction with an agonist-like phenylephrine. In our argument, this eigenmode $(5,6)$ should correspond to spontaneous vasomotion and is hard to observe in realistic mesenteric arterioles due to its fast decay. ($\mathrm{b}$) The set of eigenmode $(22,23)$ (red and blue curves in Fig. \ref{fig4}), however, exhibits strong dependence on the extracellular potassium concentrations and has different behaviors in regions $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}$, $\mathrm{\mathbf{II}}$, and $\mathrm{\mathbf{III}}$. In region $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}$, a oscillation-deactivation section, eigenvalues of modes $22$ and $23$ are distinctly separate, and no oscillating actions appear. In region $\mathrm{\mathbf{II}}$, an oscillation-activation section, the decay time of modes $(22,23)$ prolongs exponentially when increasing extracellular potassium concentrations, and is present as a dominant eigenmode at $[K]_e\simeq 36mM$. Around $[K]_e\simeq 36mM$, our analysis for eigenmode $(22,23)$ can mostly be realized as an experimental observation due to its robustness of life time. For $[K]_e\ll 36mM$, eigenmode $(22,23)$ could be smeared due to the nature of non-orthogonality of eigenmodes. In region $\mathrm{\mathbf{III}}$, as shown in Fig. (\ref{fig4}a), the real part of the eigenvalues turns into a positive value, and hence eigenmode $(22,23)$ transfers to a transient growing type. The oscillating amplitude could rise violently along the curve of the experimental set (red curve) in Fig. (\ref{fig3}b). These significant deviations from equilibrium invalidate the precision of our algorithm except for qualitative analysis. In summary, numerical results of Fig. (\ref{fig4}) show three types of
calcium oscillations of SMCs in mesenteric arterioles: the spontaneous calcium oscillation (green curves), the agonist-dependent calcium oscillation (blue curves in region $\mathrm{\mathbf{II}}$), and the agonist-dependent calcium spike (blue curves in region $\mathrm{\mathbf{III}}$) as shown in Fig. (\ref{fig4}).

\begin{figure*}[ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.415]{fig4.eps}
\caption{ Eigenvalue spectrum of single SMC in response to extracellular potassium concentrations. (a) real parts of eigenvalues for evolution time, and (b) imaginary parts of eigenvalues for oscillation periods.}\label{fig4}
\end{figure*}

Except for eigenvalue analysis of Fig. (\ref{fig4}), eigenfunctions also provide abundant information on weighting and timing of signallings associated with rhythmic oscillations of SMCs. Figures (\ref{fig5}) and (\ref{fig6}) show the component amplitude $\hat{\delta}_{\nu i}\equiv |{\delta}_{\nu i}/{\bar{\delta}}_{\nu i}|$ and component phase angle $\vartheta_{\nu i}$ of eigenmode ($22,23$) in response to extracellular potassium concentrations, respectively. Since Eq. (\ref{ty3}) is able to transform the eigenmode associated with $\delta_{\nu i}$ into an eigenmode associated with variant ionic currents $\Delta \vec{I}\sim\mathbf{\Lambda} \vec{\delta}_{\nu }$, we can evaluate the oscillation amplitude of current $\Delta I_i$ of eigenmode ($22,23$) in response to extracellular potassium concentrations, as shown in Fig. (\ref{fig7}). Figure (\ref{fig8}) illustrates phase delay regarding the oscillation for the current $\Delta I_i$ of eigenmode ($22,23$) versus extracellular potassium concentrations. We notice that all definitions of phase delay in this work are referred to the transient calcium concentration in cytosol.

Studies of signal-inhibitions and vascular mechanics have in fact suggested that there is more than
one mechanism (intracellular stores) in operation of rhythmic contractions of SMCs, e.g. a number of mechanical measurements \cite{dyn1,dyn2,dyn3,dyn4,dyn5,dyn6} have demonstrated mandatory or modulatory roles for $K^+$ channels in vasomotion in vessels such as mesenteric arteries. The activation of $cGMP$ and the calcium-dependent chloride current in vasomotion have been found in endothelium-denuded mesenteric arteries. In a voltage-dependent coupled oscillator model, the depolarization and the involvement of voltage-dependent calcium current have been proposed to be responsible for agonist-dependent vasomotion in mesenteric arteries \cite{dyn7,dyn8,dyn9}.

To investigate these underlying mechanisms for rhythmic contractions of SMCs, we employ the analysis of eigenfunctions in Figs (\ref{fig5}-\ref{fig8}) to account for correlations and synchronizing timings of signaling pathways. For the oscillating eigenmodes associated with $\delta_{\nu i}$ in Figs. (\ref{fig5}-\ref{fig6}), several findings are noted: ($\mathrm{I}$) Together with the gradually predominant oscillating properties on increasing $[K]_e$, cations $[Na]_i$ and $[K]_i$ intentionally transform from the out-phase configuration toward the in-phase synchronization with $[Ca]_i$ in Fig. (\ref{fig6}), and an inverse transform appears for anion $[Cl]_i$. This implies the growing oscillations by alternate positive and negative charge accumulations in cytosol for the membrane potentials. ($\mathrm{II}$) The definite involvement of Ryanodine ($R_{10}$, $R_{11}$, and $R_{01}$) and the $IP_3$ ($h_{IP3}$) receptors in Fig. (\ref{fig5}) reveal the significance of correlations between calcium oscillation and intracellular stores, agreeing with the experimental perspective \cite{vasoa4}. ($\mathrm{III}$) Inevitably, store-operated channels such as $P_{SOC}$ as well as $Na^+$ ions shown in Fig. (\ref{fig5}) also participate in the vasomotion. ($\mathrm{IV}$) In spite of the appearance of weak correlations between the calcium oscillation ($\sim22\%$) and the channel current $I_{BKCa}$ ($\Delta I_{BKCa}/\bar{I}_{BKCa}=0.04/2.45\sim1.5\%$) in Fig. (\ref{fig7}) for the control condition (refer to Fig. \ref{fig3}), the recessive relevance of the pathway by $p_f$ ($\sim19\%$) and $p_s$ ($\sim19\%$) in Fig. (\ref{fig5}) could still be significant. The discordance could be assumed as desynchronization effects of this channel, via regulating $p_f$ and $p_s$ to eliminate the final oscillation of $I_{BKCa}$.

