\includegraphics[scale=0.375]{fig5.eps}
\caption{ Component amplitude $\hat{\delta}_{\nu i}\equiv |{\delta}_{\nu i}/{\bar{\delta}}_{\nu i}|$ of eigenmode ($22,23$) in response to extracellular potassium concentrations.}\label{fig5}
\end{figure*}

\begin{figure*}[ht]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.375]{fig6.eps}
\caption{ Component phase angle $\vartheta_{\nu i}$ of eigenmode ($22,23$) in response to extracellular potassium concentrations..}\label{fig6}
\end{figure*}

Figures (\ref{fig7}) and (\ref{fig8}) more intuitionally illustrate the properties of eigenmode (22 and 23) associated with ionic currents $\Delta I_i$. Instead of serial causality among signal pathways, we adopt the viewpoint of multiple parallel stream flows with inter-channel couplings. The proper synchronizing timings among pathways can contribute to the prolongation of the oscillating activity, and oppositely the rhythmic oscillation could be diminished due to inappropriate signal timings or deviations, e.g diseases. For instance, in the control condition ($[K]_{e}=35.8mM$), Fig. (\ref{fig6}) implies two dominant stream flows: one stream flow for the cycle of cytosol ions by $[K^{+}]_i

with matrix components
\begin{eqnarray}
\widetilde{\mathbf{\Omega }}_{pq,i} &=&\mathbf{\Omega }_{pq,i}+\sum_{j}c_{j}
\Delta I_{GJ,j}^{\nu _{q}}\delta _{\nu _{q,i}}  \label{ty7} \\
\mathbf{\Theta }_{pq,iC} &=&\sum_{j}c_{j}\Delta I_{GJ,j}^{\nu _{q,C}}\delta
_{\nu _{q,C}}  \label{ty8}
\end{eqnarray}
Here, $I_{GJ,j}$ is the gap-junction current of ion $j$ (or of $[IP_{3}]$),
and $C$ indexes the nearby SMC coupled to the local one. Furthermore, $\widetilde{\mathbf{
\Omega }}_{pq,i}$ includes the cell couplings by $\Delta I_{GJ,j}$, the
second term in Eq. (\ref{ty7}), which is stimulated by the local\ variation of $
\delta _{\nu _{q,i}}$ ($q_{th}$ component of $\vec{\delta}_{\nu ,i}$) in SMC
$i$. We also note that $\mathbf{\Theta }_{pq,iC}$ evaluates the cell couplings stimulated by
variations of $\delta _{\nu _{q,C}}$ from nearby SMC $C$ for local SMC $i$.
Since the format of the matrix in Eq. (\ref{ty6}) remains the same as in Eq. (\ref
{ty4}), the same process for solving single SMC can be applied directly for
multiple SMCs.

\section{Numerical results and discussions}
In this section, ($\mathrm{I}$) we carry out the frequency-domain solution on the control set of SMC to recognize how the resulting eigenvalue and eigenfunction can correspond to the time-domain evolution of transient variables.
($\mathrm{II}$) By understanding frequency-domain analysis, we can continue to investigate the underlying mechanisms of rhythmicity by varying dosages of agonists (KCl) for emerging calcium oscillations; otherwise, time-domain analysis is performed to get intuitional ideas of synchronized timings  among signaling pathways, and this action also validates our approach.
($\mathrm{III}$) Lastly, we involve intercellular calcium dynamics in finite SMC clusters and attempt to explore physiological functionalities of the rhythmic oscillations of SMCs.

Mathematical algorithms were implemented in Visual C++ and were executed on HP Z800 workstation with 48GB of RAM. Relevant default values of the variables and initial parameters are defined in appendix \ref{appa}. Source codes of C++ language for time-domain and frequency-domain analyses are available online: https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B8l8iii7Z4iqWWJRLTduRl9zMVE. We also refer to JSim computations for time-domain programming: http://www.physiome.org/jsim/.

\subsection{Understanding the frequency-domain approach on the control set of SMC}
