\subsection{Frequency-domain analysis for finite SMC clusters}
 We now attempt to explore physiological functionalities of rhythmic oscillations of SMCs, especially for tissue perfusion and signaling communications among cells. For intercellular communication, we include the electro-diffusion coupling \cite{mathmodel2}, which uses the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz
(GHK) equation for ionic currents through the gap
junctions. These ionic currents were added to the membrane
potential equation and corresponding ionic flux equations as in appendices \ref{appb12}, \ref{appd}, and \ref{appf}.
Permeability was assumed to be the same for all ions. Gap
junction resistance values available from experiments \cite{gjvalue1} were
used to calculate the permeability; otherwise, $15\%$ variations of SMC volumes, as indicated in Ref. \cite{sizedep1}, were introduced to realize the inhomogeneity of cells.

Figure (\ref{fig12}) shows the frequency spectrum for homogeneous 1D clusters with varying cell numbers. The individual cell is set on the control condition ( with $[K]_e=34.8mM$), and only the neighbor atoms establish gap junctions. As indicated by green (spontaneous oscillating mode) and red (agonist-dependent oscillating mode) lines in Fig. (\ref{fig12}), the oscillation level gradually evolves into a spread band along with the increasing cell numbers. This fact infers that a broader-range timing or synchronization among cells is accessible and could facilitate rhythmical oscillations of clusters. Moreover, properties of red curves in figure (\ref{fig12}a) suggest that, due to including more interactions among cells, more transient growing states (positive frequency values) are excited, resulting in the promotion of duration periods of vasomotions. We try to alternatively recognize the inference by time-domain analysis as below.

As illustrated in Fig (\ref{fig13}a), by implementing the same condition for Fig. (\ref{fig12}), the temporal changes of $[Ca^{2+}]_i$ of a 6-SMC cluster are evaluated. In this case, $[K]_e$ is reduced to be $34.6mM$ to prepare for initially static cells. Another 6-SMC cluster, occupying the region $\mathrm{I}$ of oscillation-deactivation ($[K]_e=20mM$) of Fig. \ref{fig4} is also evaluated in Fig (\ref{fig13}b) for comparison. Before the transient stimulation $[Ca^{2+}]_i$ in both 6-SMC clusters remains static and indistinguishable for observations. With the given stimulation (suddenly raising $35\%$ calcium concentration on SMC1), however, the cluster under the oscillation-activation region $\mathrm{II}$ first arouses significant calcium sparks as shown in Fig. (\ref{fig13}a). Numerical results (not showed in the figure) indicate that Calcium spark arises from the activation of clusters of ryanodine receptors, which cause $[Ca^{2+}]_i$ to be released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. We infer that the calcium spark is attributed to the sudden transfer of an eigenmode, or equivalently, one kind of its functionality is to drive the follow-up globally-oscillating mode, supporting previous observations \cite{spark1}. For the cluster under oscillation-deactivation in Fig. (\ref{fig13}b), the stimulation dissipates fast and no signal communications among cells occur, conforming with the experiments of rat mesenteric arterial strips denuded of the endothelium \cite{wave1}: "Combined with a global stimulation of $0.3mM$ phenylephrine through the superfusion system, the local stimulations
induced propagation of an intercellular calcium wave, while there was no propagation when the artery was in its resting state.".

