We further include the inhomogeneity of SMCS for inevitable biological complexity. Here, $15\%$ stochastic variations of SMC volumes \cite{sizedep1} are introduced for both frequency-domain and time-domain analyses. Fig. (\ref{fig14}a) depicts similar properties for the agonist-dependent oscillating modes (red lines), although the growing mode seems to be more easily excited due to the fluctuation of cell volumes; otherwise, it is noted that the spontaneous oscillating modes (green lines) remain relatively insensitive to cell number as well as cell uniformity. Figure (\ref{fig14}b) exhibits a broader but less dense level spectrum, versus Fig. (\ref{fig12}b). This fact could imply that the vasomotion in inhomogeneous clusters can decay faster than the homogeneous ones due to the well-separated oscillating levels.

By the same token, we perform the time-domain analysis to recognize the influences of cell uniformity. One inhomogeneous 6-SMC cluster under the oscillation-activation region (region $\mathrm{II}$ in Fig \ref{fig4}) is evaluated as in Fig. (\ref{fig15}a), and another inhomogeneous cluster under oscillation-deactivation region (region $\mathrm{I}$ in Fig \ref{fig4}) is analyzed as in Fig. (\ref{fig15}b). In the case of Fig. (\ref{fig15}a), $[K]_e$ is set to be $35.0mM$ in preparation for initially static cells. In the case of Fig. (\ref{fig15}b), $[K]_e$ is reduced to be $20mM$ to arrange the oscillation-deactivation condition.
As indicated in Fig. (\ref{fig15}b), the stimulation dissipates fast and no signal communications among cells occur as well. In Fig. (\ref{fig15}a), we find that the stimulation on inhomogeneous clusters decays relatively faster than that on homogeneous ones; otherwise, the signaling delivery among cells presents properties differing from the molecular diffusions that characterize a frog-leap manner (from SMC1 to SMC3), depending on the specific inhomogeneity, or equivalently, the specific oscillating eigenmodes. Our analysis agrees well with statements in the literature\cite{ex3,ex5}.

